[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] The preprocessing pipeline used can often have large effects on the conclusions drawn from the downstream analysis.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Thus, representation and quality of data is necessary before running any analysis.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] If there is a high proportion of irrelevant and redundant information present or noisy and unreliable data, then knowledge discovery during the training phase may be more difficult.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Data preparation and filtering steps can take a considerable amount of processing time.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Examples of methods used in data preprocessing include cleaning, instance selection, normalization, one-hot encoding, data transformation, feature extraction and feature selection.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Data preprocessing allows for the removal of unwanted data with the use of data cleaning, this allows the user to have a dataset to contain more valuable information after the preprocessing stage for data manipulation later in the data mining process.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Editing such dataset to either correct data corruption or human error is a crucial step to get accurate quantifiers like true positives, true negatives, false positives and false negatives found in a confusion matrix that are commonly used for a medical diagnosis.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Users are able to join data files together and use preprocessing to filter any unnecessary noise from the data which can allow for higher accuracy.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Users use Python programming scripts accompanied by the pandas library which gives them the ability to import data from a comma-separated values as a data-frame.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] The data-frame is then used to manipulate data that can be challenging otherwise to do in Excel.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Pandas (software) which is a powerful tool that allows for data analysis and manipulation; which makes data visualizations, statistical operations and much more, a lot easier.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Many also use the R programming language to do such tasks as well.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] The reason why a user transforms existing files into a new one is because of many reasons.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Aspects of data preprocessing may include imputing missing values, aggregating numerical quantities and transforming continuous data into categories (data binning).
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] More advanced techniques like principal component analysis and feature selection are working with statistical formulas and are applied to complex datasets which are recorded by GPS trackers and motion capture devices.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Semantic data mining is a subset of data mining that specifically seeks to incorporate domain knowledge, such as formal semantics, into the data mining process.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Domain knowledge is the knowledge of the environment the data was processed in.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Domain knowledge can have a positive influence on many aspects of data mining, such as filtering out redundant or inconsistent data during the preprocessing phase.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Domain knowledge also works as constraint.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] It does this by using working as set of prior knowledge to reduce the space required for searching and acting as a guide to the data.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Simply put, semantic preprocessing seeks to filter data using the original environment of said data more correctly and efficiently.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] There are increasingly complex problems which are asking to be solved by more elaborate techniques to better analyze existing information.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Instead of creating a simple script for aggregating different numerical values into a single value, it make sense to focus on semantic based data preprocessing.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] The idea is to build a dedicated ontology, which explains on a higher level what the problem is about.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] In regards to semantic data mining and semantic pre-processing, ontologies are a way to conceptualize and formally define semantic knowledge and data.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] The Protégé (software) is the standard tool for constructing an ontology.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] In general, the use of ontologies bridges the gaps between data, applications, algorithms, and results that occur from semantic mismatches.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] As a result, semantic data mining combined with ontology has many applications where semantic ambiguity can impact the usefulness and efficiency of data systems.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Applications include the medical field, language processing, banking, and even tutoring, among many more.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] There are various strengths to using a semantic data mining and ontological based approach.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] As previously mentioned, these tools can help during the per-processing phase by filtering out non-desirable data from the data set.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Additionally, well-structured formal semantics integrated into well designed ontologies can return powerful data that can be easily read and processed by machines.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] A specifically useful example of this exists in the medical use of semantic data processing.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] As an example, a patient is having a medical emergency and is being rushed to hospital.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] The emergency responders are trying to figure out the best medicine to administer to help the patient.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Under normal data processing, scouring all the patient’s medical data to ensure they are getting the best treatment could take too long and risk the patients’ health or even life.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] However, using semantically processed ontologies, the first responders could save the patient’s life.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Tools like a semantic reasoner can use ontology to infer the what best medicine to administer to the patient is based on their medical history, such as if they have a certain cancer or other conditions, simply by examining the natural language used in the patient's medical records.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] This would allow the first responders to quickly and efficiently search for medicine without having worry about the patient’s medical history themselves, as the semantic reasoner would already have analyzed this data and found solutions.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] In general, this illustrates the incredible strength of using semantic data mining and ontologies.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] They allow for quicker and more efficient data extraction on the user side, as the user has fewer variables to account for, since the semantically pre-processed data and ontology built for the data have already accounted for many of these variables.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] However, there are some drawbacks to this approach.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Namely, it requires a high amount of computational power and complexity, even with relatively small data sets.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] This could result in higher costs and increased difficulties in building and maintaining semantic data processing systems.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] This can be mitigated somewhat if the data set is already well organized and formatted, but even then, the complexity is still higher when compared to standard data processing.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Below is a simple a diagram combining some of the processes, in particular semantic data mining and their use in ontology.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] The diagram depicts a data set being broken up into two parts: the characteristics of its domain, or domain knowledge, and then the actual acquired data.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] The domain characteristics are then processed to become user understood domain knowledge that can be applied to the data.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Meanwhile, the data set is processed and stored so that the domain knowledge can applied to it, so that the process may continue.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] From there, the ontology can be used to analyze data and process results.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Fuzzy preprocessing is another, more advanced technique for solving complex problems.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Fuzzy preprocessing and fuzzy data mining make use of fuzzy sets.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] These data sets are composed of two elements: a set and a membership function for the set which comprises 0 and 1.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Fuzzy preprocessing uses this fuzzy data set to ground numerical values with linguistic information.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Raw data is then transformed into natural language.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Ultimately, fuzzy data mining's goal is to help deal with inexact information, such as an incomplete database.
[src:feature-engineering/data-preprocessing] Currently fuzzy preprocessing, as well as other fuzzy based data mining techniques see frequent use with neural networks and artificial intelligence.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Methods are commonly divided into linear and nonlinear approaches.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Linear approaches can be further divided into feature selection and feature extraction.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Dimensionality reduction can be used for noise reduction, data visualization, cluster analysis, or as an intermediate step to facilitate other analyses.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The process of feature selection aims to find a suitable subset of the input variables (*features*, or *attributes*) for the task at hand.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The three strategies are: the *filter* strategy (e.g., information gain), the *wrapper* strategy (e.g., accuracy-guided search), and the *embedded* strategy (features are added or removed while building the model based on prediction errors).
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Data analysis such as regression or classification can be done in the reduced space more accurately than in the original space.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Feature projection (also called feature extraction) transforms the data from the high-dimensional space to a space of fewer dimensions.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The data transformation may be linear, as in principal component analysis (PCA), but many nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques also exist.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] For multidimensional data, tensor representation can be used in dimensionality reduction through multilinear subspace learning.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The main linear technique for dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis, performs a linear mapping of the data to a lower-dimensional space in such a way that the variance of the data in the low-dimensional representation is maximized.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] In practice, the covariance (and sometimes the correlation) matrix of the data is constructed and the eigenvectors on this matrix are computed.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The eigenvectors that correspond to the largest eigenvalues (the principal components) can now be used to reconstruct a large fraction of the variance of the original data.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Moreover, the first few eigenvectors can often be interpreted in terms of the large-scale physical behavior of the system, because they often contribute the vast majority of the system's energy, especially in low-dimensional systems.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Still, this must be proved on a case-by-case basis as not all systems exhibit this behavior.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The original space (with dimension of the number of points) has been reduced (with data loss, but hopefully retaining the most important variance) to the space spanned by a few eigenvectors.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] NMF decomposes a non-negative matrix to the product of two non-negative ones, which has been a promising tool in fields where only non-negative signals exist, such as astronomy.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] With a stable component basis during construction, and a linear modeling process, sequential NMF is able to preserve the flux in direct imaging of circumstellar structures in astronomy, as one of the methods of detecting exoplanets, especially for the direct imaging of circumstellar discs.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] In comparison with PCA, NMF does not remove the mean of the matrices, which leads to physical non-negative fluxes; therefore NMF is able to preserve more information than PCA as demonstrated by Ren et al.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Principal component analysis can be employed in a nonlinear way by means of the kernel trick.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is capable of constructing nonlinear mappings that maximize the variance in the data.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is called kernel PCA.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Other prominent nonlinear techniques include manifold learning techniques such as Isomap, locally linear embedding (LLE), Hessian LLE, Laplacian eigenmaps, and methods based on tangent space analysis.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] More recently, techniques have been proposed that, instead of defining a fixed kernel, try to learn the kernel using semidefinite programming.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The most prominent example of such a technique is maximum variance unfolding (MVU).
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The central idea of MVU is to exactly preserve all pairwise distances between nearest neighbors (in the inner product space) while maximizing the distances between points that are not nearest neighbors.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] An alternative approach to neighborhood preservation is through the minimization of a cost function that measures differences between distances in the input and output spaces.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] A different approach to nonlinear dimensionality reduction is through the use of autoencoders, a special kind of feedforward neural networks with a bottleneck hidden layer.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The training of deep encoders is typically performed using a greedy layer-wise pre-training (e.g., using a stack of restricted Boltzmann machines) that is followed by a finetuning stage based on backpropagation.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is a generalization of Fisher's linear discriminant, a method used in statistics, pattern recognition, and machine learning to find a linear combination of features that characterizes or separates two or more classes of objects or events.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] GDA deals with nonlinear discriminant analysis using kernel function operator.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] The underlying theory is close to the support-vector machines (SVM) insofar as the GDA method provides a mapping of the input vectors into high-dimensional feature space.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Similar to LDA, the objective of GDA is to find a projection for the features into a lower dimensional space by maximizing the ratio of between-class scatter to within-class scatter.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Autoencoders can be used to learn nonlinear dimension reduction functions and codings together with an inverse function from the coding to the original representation.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique useful for the visualization of high-dimensional datasets.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] It is not recommended for use in analysis such as clustering or outlier detection since it does not necessarily preserve densities or distances well.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] Visually, it is similar to t-SNE, but it assumes that the data is uniformly distributed on a locally connected Riemannian manifold and that the Riemannian metric is locally constant or approximately locally constant.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] For high-dimensional datasets, dimension reduction is usually performed prior to applying a *k*-nearest neighbors (*k*-NN) algorithm in order to mitigate the curse of dimensionality.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] In machine learning, this process is also called low-dimensional embedding.
[src:feature-engineering/dimensionality-reduction] A dimensionality reduction technique that is sometimes used in neuroscience is maximally informative dimensions, which finds a lower-dimensional representation of a dataset such that as much information as possible about the original data is preserved.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Beyond machine learning, the principles of feature engineering are applied in various scientific fields, including physics.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] For example, physicists construct dimensionless numbers such as the Reynolds number in fluid dynamics, the Nusselt number in heat transfer, and the Archimedes number in sedimentation.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] They also develop first approximations of solutions, such as analytical solutions for the strength of materials in mechanics.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] One of the applications of feature engineering has been clustering of feature-objects or sample-objects in a dataset.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Especially, feature engineering based on matrix decomposition has been extensively used for data clustering under non-negativity constraints on the feature coefficients.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] These include *Non-Negative Matrix Factorization* (NMF), *Non-Negative Matrix-Tri Factorization* (NMTF), *Non-Negative Tensor Decomposition/Factorization* (NTF/NTD), etc.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] The non-negativity constraints on coefficients of the feature vectors mined by the above-stated algorithms yields a part-based representation, and different factor matrices exhibit natural clustering properties.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Several extensions of the above-stated feature engineering methods have been reported in literature, including *orthogonality-constrained factorization* for hard clustering, and *manifold learning* to overcome inherent issues with these algorithms.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Other classes of feature engineering algorithms include leveraging a common hidden structure across multiple inter-related datasets to obtain a consensus (common) clustering scheme.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] An example is *Multi-view Classification based on Consensus Matrix Decomposition* (MCMD), which mines a common clustering scheme across multiple datasets.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Coupled matrix and tensor decompositions are popular in multi-view feature engineering.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Feature engineering in machine learning and statistical modeling involves selecting, creating, transforming, and extracting data features.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Even relatively insignificant features may contribute to a model.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Feature selection can reduce the number of features to prevent a model from becoming too specific to the training data set (overfitting).
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Feature explosion occurs when the number of identified features is too large for effective model estimation or optimization.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Feature explosion can be limited via techniques such as regularization, kernel methods, and feature selection.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Automation of feature engineering is a research topic that dates back to the 1990s.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Machine learning software that incorporates automated feature engineering has been commercially available since 2016.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Multi-relational Decision Tree Learning (MRDTL) extends traditional decision tree methods to relational databases, handling complex data relationships across tables.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] It innovatively uses selection graphs as decision nodes, refined systematically until a specific termination criterion is reached.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Most MRDTL studies base implementations on relational databases, which results in many redundant operations.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] These redundancies can be reduced by using techniques such as tuple id propagation.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] The deep feature synthesis (DFS) algorithm beat 615 of 906 human teams in a competition.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] The feature store is where the features are stored and organized for the explicit purpose of being used to either train models (by data scientists) or make predictions (by applications that have a trained model).
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] A feature store includes the ability to store code used to generate features, apply the code to raw data, and serve those features to models upon request.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Useful capabilities include feature versioning and policies governing the circumstances under which features can be used.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Feature stores can be standalone software tools or built into machine learning platforms.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Feature engineering can be a time-consuming and error-prone process, as it requires domain expertise and often involves trial and error.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] Deep learning algorithms may be used to process a large raw dataset without having to resort to feature engineering.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] However, deep learning algorithms still require careful preprocessing and cleaning of the input data.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-engineering] In addition, choosing the right architecture, hyperparameters, and optimization algorithm for a deep neural network can be a challenging and iterative process.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Since the range of values of raw data varies widely, in some machine learning algorithms, objective functions will not work properly without normalization.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] For example, many classifiers calculate the distance between two points by the Euclidean distance.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] If one of the features has a broad range of values, the distance will be governed by this particular feature.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Therefore, the range of all features should be normalized so that each feature contributes approximately proportionately to the final distance.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Another reason why feature scaling is applied is that gradient descent converges much faster with feature scaling than without it.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] It's also important to apply feature scaling if regularization is used as part of the loss function (so that coefficients are penalized appropriately).
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Empirically, feature scaling can improve the convergence speed of stochastic gradient descent.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] In support vector machines, it can reduce the time to find support vectors.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Feature scaling is also often used in applications involving distances and similarities between data points, such as clustering and similarity search.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] As an example, the K-means clustering algorithm is sensitive to feature scales.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Also known as min-max scaling or min-max normalization, rescaling is the simplest method and consists in rescaling the range of features to scale the range in [0, 1] or [−1, 1].
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Selecting the target range depends on the nature of the data.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] where x is an original value, $x'$ is the normalized value.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] For example, suppose that we have the students' weight data, and the students' weights span [160 pounds, 200 pounds].
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] To rescale this data, we first subtract 160 from each student's weight and divide the result by 40 (the difference between the maximum and minimum weights).
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] where x is an original value, $x'$ is the normalized value, ${\bar {x}}={\text{average}}(x)$ is the mean of that feature vector.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] There is another form of the means normalization which divides by the standard deviation which is also called standardization.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] In machine learning, we can handle various types of data, e.g. audio signals and pixel values for image data, and this data can include multiple dimensions.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Feature standardization makes the values of each feature in the data have zero-mean (when subtracting the mean in the numerator) and unit-variance.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] This method is widely used for normalization in many machine learning algorithms (e.g., support vector machines, logistic regression, and artificial neural networks).
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] The general method of calculation is to determine the distribution mean and standard deviation for each feature.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Next we subtract the mean from each feature.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Then we divide the values (mean is already subtracted) of each feature by its standard deviation.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Where x is the original feature vector, ${\bar {x}}={\text{average}}(x)$ is the mean of that feature vector, and $\sigma$ is its standard deviation.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Unit vector normalization regards each individual data point as a vector, and divide each by its vector norm, to obtain $x'=x/\|x\|$ .
[src:feature-engineering/feature-scaling] Any vector norm can be used, but the most common ones are the L1 norm and the L2 norm.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] In machine learning, **feature selection** is the process of selecting a subset of relevant features (variables, predictors) for use in model construction.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The central premise when using feature selection is that data sometimes contains features that are *redundant* or *irrelevant*, and can thus be removed without incurring much loss of information.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Redundancy and irrelevance are two distinct notions, since one relevant feature may be redundant in the presence of another relevant feature with which it is strongly correlated.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Feature extraction creates new features from functions of the original features, whereas feature selection finds a subset of the features.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Feature selection techniques are often used in domains where there are many features and comparatively few samples (data points).
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] A feature selection algorithm can be seen as the combination of a search technique for proposing new feature subsets, along with an evaluation measure which scores the different feature subsets.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The simplest algorithm is to test each possible subset of features finding the one which minimizes the error rate.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] This is an exhaustive search of the space, and is computationally intractable for all but the smallest of feature sets.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The choice of evaluation metric heavily influences the algorithm, and it is these evaluation metrics which distinguish between the three main categories of feature selection algorithms: wrappers, filters and embedded methods.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] In traditional regression analysis, the most popular form of feature selection is stepwise regression, which is a wrapper technique.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] It is a greedy algorithm that adds the best feature (or deletes the worst feature) at each round.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The main control issue is deciding when to stop the algorithm.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] In machine learning, this is typically done by cross-validation.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] In statistics, some criteria are optimized.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] This leads to the inherent problem of nesting.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] More robust methods have been explored, such as branch and bound and piecewise linear network.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Subset selection evaluates a subset of features as a group for suitability.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Subset selection algorithms can be broken up into wrappers, filters, and embedded methods.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Wrappers use a search algorithm to search through the space of possible features and evaluate each subset by running a model on the subset.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Wrappers can be computationally expensive and have a risk of over fitting to the model.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Filters are similar to wrappers in the search approach, but instead of evaluating against a model, a simpler filter is evaluated.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Embedded techniques are embedded in, and specific to, a model.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Many popular search approaches use greedy hill climbing, which iteratively evaluates a candidate subset of features, then modifies the subset and evaluates if the new subset is an improvement over the old.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Evaluation of the subsets requires a scoring metric that grades a subset of features.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Exhaustive search is generally impractical, so at some implementor (or operator) defined stopping point, the subset of features with the highest score discovered up to that point is selected as the satisfactory feature subset.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The stopping criterion varies by algorithm; possible criteria include: a subset score exceeds a threshold, a program's maximum allowed run time has been surpassed, etc.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Alternative search-based techniques are based on targeted projection pursuit which finds low-dimensional projections of the data that score highly: the features that have the largest projections in the lower-dimensional space are then selected.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] These scores are computed between a candidate feature (or set of features) and the desired output category.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] There are, however, true metrics that are a simple function of the mutual information; see here.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The choice of optimality criteria is difficult as there are multiple objectives in a feature selection task.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Many common criteria incorporate a measure of accuracy, penalised by the number of features selected.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Examples include Akaike information criterion (AIC) and Mallows's *Cp*, which have a penalty of 2 for each added feature.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] AIC is based on information theory, and is effectively derived via the maximum entropy principle.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] A maximum entropy rate criterion may also be used to select the most relevant subset of features.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Filter feature selection is a specific case of a more general paradigm called structure learning.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Feature selection finds the relevant feature set for a specific target variable whereas structure learning finds the relationships between all the variables, usually by expressing these relationships as a graph.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The most common structure learning algorithms assume the data is generated by a Bayesian Network, and so the structure is a directed graphical model.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The optimal solution to the filter feature selection problem is the Markov blanket of the target node, and in a Bayesian Network, there is a unique Markov Blanket for each node.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] There are different Feature Selection mechanisms around that utilize mutual information for scoring the different features.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The simplest approach uses the mutual information as the "derived" score.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] However, there are different approaches, that try to reduce the redundancy between features.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Peng *et al.* proposed a feature selection method that can use either mutual information, correlation, or distance/similarity scores to select features.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The aim is to penalise a feature's relevancy by its redundancy in the presence of the other selected features.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Suppose that there are n full-set features.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Let *xi* be the set membership indicator function for feature *fi*, so that *xi*=1 indicates presence and *xi*=0 indicates absence of the feature *fi* in the globally optimal feature set.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The mRMR algorithm is an approximation of the theoretically optimal maximum-dependency feature selection algorithm that maximizes the mutual information between the joint distribution of the selected features and the classification variable.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] As mRMR approximates the combinatorial estimation problem with a series of much smaller problems, each of which only involves two variables, it thus uses pairwise joint probabilities which are more robust.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] In certain situations the algorithm may underestimate the usefulness of features as it has no way to measure interactions between features which can increase relevancy.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] This can lead to poor performance when the features are individually useless, but are useful when combined (a pathological case is found when the class is a parity function of the features).
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Overall the algorithm is more efficient (in terms of the amount of data required) than the theoretically optimal max-dependency selection, yet produces a feature set with little pairwise redundancy.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] mRMR is an instance of a large class of filter methods which trade off between relevancy and redundancy in different ways.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] mRMR is a typical example of an incremental greedy strategy for feature selection: once a feature has been selected, it cannot be deselected at a later stage.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] where $F_{n\times 1}=[I(f_{1};c),\ldots ,I(f_{n};c)]^{T}$ is the vector of feature relevancy assuming there are n features in total, $H_{n\times n}=[I(f_{i};f_{j})]_{i,j=1\ldots n}$ is the matrix of feature pairwise redundancy, and $\mathbf {x} _{n\times 1}$ represents relative feature weights.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] QPFS is solved via quadratic programming.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] It is recently shown that QFPS is biased towards features with smaller entropy, due to its placement of the feature self redundancy term $I(f_{i};f_{i})$ on the diagonal of H.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] An advantage of SPECCMI is that it can be solved simply via finding the dominant eigenvector of Q, thus is very scalable.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] SPECCMI also handles second-order feature interaction.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] In a study of different scores Brown et al. recommended the joint mutual information as a good score for feature selection.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The score tries to find the feature, that adds the most new information to the already selected features, in order to avoid redundancy.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The score uses the conditional mutual information and the mutual information to estimate the redundancy between the already selected features ( $f_{j}\in S$ ) and the feature under investigation ( $f_{i}$ ).
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] For high-dimensional and small sample data (e.g., dimensionality > 105 and the number of samples < 103), the Hilbert-Schmidt Independence Criterion Lasso (HSIC Lasso) is useful.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] HSIC always takes a non-negative value, and is zero if and only if two random variables are statistically independent when a universal reproducing kernel such as the Gaussian kernel is used.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] where $\|\cdot \|_{F}$ is the Frobenius norm.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The optimization problem is a Lasso problem, and thus it can be efficiently solved with a state-of-the-art Lasso solver such as the dual augmented Lagrangian method.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The correlation feature selection (CFS) measure evaluates subsets of features on the basis of the following hypothesis: "Good feature subsets contain features highly correlated with the classification, yet uncorrelated to each other".
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Here, ${\overline {r_{cf}}}$ is the average value of all feature-classification correlations, and ${\overline {r_{ff}}}$ is the average value of all feature-feature correlations.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The $r_{cf_{i}}$ and $r_{f_{i}f_{j}}$ variables are referred to as correlations, but are not necessarily Pearson's correlation coefficient or Spearman's ρ.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Hall's dissertation uses neither of these, but uses three different measures of relatedness, minimum description length (MDL), symmetrical uncertainty, and relief.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The combinatorial problems above are, in fact, mixed 0–1 linear programming problems that can be solved by using branch-and-bound algorithms.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The features from a decision tree or a tree ensemble are shown to be redundant.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] A recent method called regularized tree can be used for feature subset selection.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Regularized trees penalize using a variable similar to the variables selected at previous tree nodes for splitting the current node.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Regularized trees only need build one tree model (or one tree ensemble model) and thus are computationally efficient.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Regularized trees naturally handle numerical and categorical features, interactions and nonlinearities.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] They are invariant to attribute scales (units) and insensitive to outliers, and thus, require little data preprocessing such as normalization.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Regularized random forest (RRF) is one type of regularized trees.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The guided RRF is an enhanced RRF which is guided by the importance scores from an ordinary random forest.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] A metaheuristic is a general description of an algorithm dedicated to solve difficult (typically NP-hard problem) optimization problems for which there is no classical solving methods.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Generally, a metaheuristic is a stochastic algorithm tending to reach a global optimum.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] There are many metaheuristics, from a simple local search to a complex global search algorithm.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The feature selection methods are typically presented in three classes based on how they combine the selection algorithm and the model building.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Filter type methods select variables regardless of the model.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] They are based only on general features like the correlation with the variable to predict.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Filter methods suppress the least interesting variables.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] The other variables will be part of a classification or a regression model used to classify or to predict data.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] These methods are particularly effective in computation time and robust to overfitting.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Filter methods tend to select redundant variables when they do not consider the relationships between variables.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] However, more elaborate features try to minimize this problem by removing variables highly correlated to each other, such as the Fast Correlation Based Filter (FCBF) algorithm.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Wrapper methods evaluate subsets of variables which allows, unlike filter approaches, to detect the possible interactions amongst variables.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Embedded methods have been recently proposed that try to combine the advantages of both previous methods.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] A learning algorithm takes advantage of its own variable selection process and performs feature selection and classification simultaneously, such as the FRMT algorithm.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] This is a survey of the application of feature selection metaheuristics lately used in the literature.
[src:feature-engineering/feature-selection] Some learning algorithms perform feature selection as part of their overall operation.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] In digital circuits and machine learning, a **one-hot** is a group of bits among which the legal combinations of values are only those with a single high (1) bit and all the others low (0).
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] A similar implementation in which all bits are '1' except one '0' is sometimes called **one-cold**.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] In statistics, dummy variables represent a similar technique for representing categorical data.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] One-hot encoding is often used for indicating the state of a state machine.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] When using binary, a decoder is needed to determine the state.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] A one-hot state machine, however, does not need a decoder as the state machine is in the *n*th state if, and only if, the *n*th bit is high.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] A ring counter with 15 sequentially ordered states is an example of a state machine.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] A 'one-hot' implementation would have 15 flip-flops chained in series with the Q output of each flip-flop connected to the D input of the next and the D input of the first flip-flop connected to the Q output of the 15th flip-flop.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] The first flip-flop in the chain represents the first state, the second represents the second state, and so on to the 15th flip-flop, which represents the last state.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] Upon reset of the state machine all of the flip-flops are reset to '0' except the first in the chain, which is set to '1'.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] The next clock edge arriving at the flip-flops advances the one 'hot' bit to the second flip-flop.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] The 'hot' bit advances in this way until the 15th state, after which the state machine returns to the first state.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] An address decoder converts from binary to one-hot representation.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] A priority encoder converts from one-hot representation to binary.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] In natural language processing, a one-hot vector is a 1 × *N* matrix (vector) used to distinguish each word in a vocabulary from every other word in the vocabulary.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] The vector consists of 0s in all cells with the exception of a single 1 in a cell used uniquely to identify the word.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] One-hot encoding ensures that machine learning does not assume that higher numbers are more important.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] For example, the value '8' is bigger than the value '1', but that does not make '8' more important than '1'.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] The same is true for words: the value 'laughter' is not more important than 'laugh'.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] In machine learning, one-hot encoding is a frequently used method to deal with categorical data.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] Because many machine learning models need their input variables to be numeric, categorical variables need to be transformed in the pre-processing part.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] Categorical data can be either nominal or ordinal.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] Ordinal data has a ranked order for its values and can therefore be converted to numerical data through ordinal encoding.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] An example of ordinal data would be the ratings on a test ranging from A to F, which could be ranked using numbers from 6 to 1.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] Since there is no quantitative relationship between nominal variables' individual values, using ordinal encoding can potentially create a fictional ordinal relationship in the data.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] Therefore, one-hot encoding is often applied to nominal variables, in order to improve the performance of the algorithm.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] For each unique value in the original categorical column, a new column is created in this method.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] These dummy variables are then filled up with zeros and ones (1 meaning TRUE, 0 meaning FALSE).
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] Because this process creates multiple new variables, it is prone to creating a 'big p' problem (too many predictors) if there are many unique values in the original column.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] Another downside of one-hot encoding is that it causes multicollinearity between the individual variables, which potentially reduces the model's accuracy.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] Also, if the categorical variable is an output variable, you may want to convert the values back into a categorical form in order to present them in your application.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] In practical usage, this transformation is often directly performed by a function that takes categorical data as an input and outputs the corresponding dummy variables.
[src:feature-engineering/one-hot] An example would be the dummyVars function of the Caret library in R.
